Prompt:

Act as an expert React developer and UI/UX designer. Create a single-file React application for a highly technical Real-time Transaction Dashboard (GBM Gateway). Use Tailwind CSS for styling and lucide-react for icons.

The dashboard should have a modern, clean, light-theme aesthetic (using slate, white, and subtle colored accents for status) and include the following features:

1. Layout & Header:

A top header displaying the system status, shift start time, and high-level live metrics (Total Volume, Health Percentage, Active Issues).

Include toggle buttons in the header to switch the main view between "GC Architecture" and "Event Stream".

Include toggle buttons to show/hide a bottom "Log" panel and a right "Incident" sidebar.

2. Main View - Architecture Diagram:

Create a visual system architecture diagram that auto-scales to fit the screen.

The flow should consist of: A "Gold Copy Data Store" feeding into 4 sequential processing stages (Dispatcher, Scenario, Payload, Connect).

Below the stages, show linked Kafka Topics (T24, T24-Scenario, T24-Payload).

The flow should end at a large "Event Store" node.

Crucial: Use animated SVG paths (with moving dots/circles) to represent data continuously flowing between these components.

Each processing stage node should display live "OK" and "ERR" counters.

3. Main View - Event Stream:

A list view showing individual active transactions.

Each transaction card should display its ID, type (e.g., FX_TRADE), and a visual progress bar indicating its current step through the 4 processing stages.

4. Collapsible Panels:

Bottom Panel (Terminal): A dark-themed, mono-spaced terminal window that auto-scrolls, showing simulated real-time Kafka ingest logs.

Right Sidebar (Incidents): A red-themed list showing details of any transactions that failed, acting as a real-time LIFO audit trail.

5. Simulation Engine:

Write a useEffect simulation loop that generates a new random financial transaction every ~2-3 seconds.

Progress these transactions step-by-step through the 4 stages.

Introduce a 10% random failure rate. When a transaction fails, it should halt progress, increment the "ERR" metric for that specific stage, push an error entry to the Incident sidebar, and turn red in the Event Stream view.

Ensure successful transactions increment the "OK" metrics and eventually disappear from the active stream after a few seconds.
